The universal property of the product P =   \prod _{j\in  J} X_j with projections P \xrightarrow {\pi _k} X_k is that, for any
  object Z equipped with morphisms Z\xrightarrow {\tau _k} X_k, there exists a unique
  morphism Z\to  P making the following diagrams commute:




    \usepackage{tikz, tikz-cd, mathtools, amssymb}
  \usetikzlibrary{shapes.geometric}
  \usetikzlibrary{calc}
  \usetikzlibrary{matrix}
  \usetikzlibrary{decorations.markings}

  \tikzset{
    % basics
    square/.style={draw, regular polygon, regular polygon sides=4},
    triangle/.style={draw, regular polygon, regular polygon sides=3},
  }

  \tikzset{
    % string diagrams
    state/.style={triangle, shape border rotate=180, anchor=north},
    costate/.style={triangle, anchor=south},
    morphism/.style={draw, rectangle},
    over/.style={
      draw=white,
      double=black,
      % default is .4pt
      line width=1.2pt,
      double distance=.4pt,
      text=black
    },
  }

  \tikzset{ 
    % tables
    % https://tikz.net/tikz-table/
    table/.style={
        matrix of nodes,
        row sep=-\pgflinewidth,
        column sep=-\pgflinewidth,
        nodes={
            rectangle,
            draw=black,
            align=center
        },
        minimum height=1.5em,
        text depth=0.5ex,
        text height=2ex,
        nodes in empty cells,
%%
        every even row/.style={
            nodes={fill=gray!20}
        },
        column 1/.style={
            nodes={font=\bfseries}
        },
        row 1/.style={
            nodes={
                fill=black,
                text=white,
                font=\bfseries
            }
        }
    }
  }


    \begin {tikzcd}
    Z\ar [dr, "\tau _j"]\ar [d, dashed, "\exists  !"'] \\
    P\ar [r, "\pi _j"'] & X_j\makebox [0pt][l]{.}
    \end {tikzcd}

When J is the ordinal category 2, hence the diagram is of
  shape \bullet \,\bullet , and so the product is of two objects X and Y,
  this property has the following nice form:




    \usepackage{tikz, tikz-cd, mathtools, amssymb}
  \usetikzlibrary{shapes.geometric}
  \usetikzlibrary{calc}
  \usetikzlibrary{matrix}
  \usetikzlibrary{decorations.markings}

  \tikzset{
    % basics
    square/.style={draw, regular polygon, regular polygon sides=4},
    triangle/.style={draw, regular polygon, regular polygon sides=3},
  }

  \tikzset{
    % string diagrams
    state/.style={triangle, shape border rotate=180, anchor=north},
    costate/.style={triangle, anchor=south},
    morphism/.style={draw, rectangle},
    over/.style={
      draw=white,
      double=black,
      % default is .4pt
      line width=1.2pt,
      double distance=.4pt,
      text=black
    },
  }

  \tikzset{ 
    % tables
    % https://tikz.net/tikz-table/
    table/.style={
        matrix of nodes,
        row sep=-\pgflinewidth,
        column sep=-\pgflinewidth,
        nodes={
            rectangle,
            draw=black,
            align=center
        },
        minimum height=1.5em,
        text depth=0.5ex,
        text height=2ex,
        nodes in empty cells,
%%
        every even row/.style={
            nodes={fill=gray!20}
        },
        column 1/.style={
            nodes={font=\bfseries}
        },
        row 1/.style={
            nodes={
                fill=black,
                text=white,
                font=\bfseries
            }
        }
    }
  }


    \begin {tikzcd}
    & Z\ar [ddl, bend right, "f"']\ar [ddr, bend left, "g"]\ar [d, dashed, "\exists  !"] \\
    & X\times  Y\ar [dl, "\pi _X"]\ar [dr, "\pi _Y"'] \\
    X & & Y\makebox [0pt][l]{.}
    \end {tikzcd}
